tc_game_config_files.template:
# -------------------------------- # Geyser Configuration File # # A bridge between Minecraft: Bedrock Edition and Minecraft: Java Edition. # # GitHub: https://github.com/GeyserMC/Geyser # Discord: https://discord.geysermc.org/ # --------------------------------
bedrock: # The IP address that will listen for connections. # There is no reason to change this unless you want to limit what IPs can connect to your server. address: $[Service.IpAddress] # The port that will listen for connections port: 19132 # Some hosting services change your Java port everytime you start the server and require the same port to be used for Bedrock. # This option makes the Bedrock port the same as the Java port every time you start the server. # This option is for the plugin version only. clone-remote-port: true # The MOTD that will be broadcasted to Minecraft: Bedrock Edition clients. This is irrelevant if "passthrough-motd" is set to true # If either of these are empty, the respective string will default to "Geyser" motd1: "Geyser" motd2: "Another Geyser server." # The Server Name that will be sent to Minecraft: Bedrock Edition clients. This is visible in both the pause menu and the settings menu. server-name: "Geyser" # How much to compress network traffic to the Bedrock client. The higher the number, the more CPU usage used, but # the smaller the bandwidth used. Does not have any effect below -1 or above 9. Set to -1 to disable. compression-level: 6 # Whether to enable PROXY protocol or not for clients. You DO NOT WANT this feature unless you run UDP reverse proxy # in front of your Geyser instance. enable-proxy-protocol: false # A list of allowed PROXY protocol speaking proxy IP addresses/subnets. Only effective when "enable-proxy-protocol" is enabled, and # should really only be used when you are not able to use a proper firewall (usually true with shared hosting providers etc.). # Keeping this list empty means there is no IP address whitelist. # Both IP addresses and subnets are supported. #proxy-protocol-whitelisted-ips: [ "127.0.0.1", "172.18.0.0/16" ] remote: # The IP address of the remote (Java Edition) server # If it is "auto", for standalone version the remote address will be set to 127.0.0.1, # for plugin versions, it is recommended to keep this as "auto" so Geyser will automatically configure address, port, and auth-type. # Leave as "auto" if floodgate is installed. address: auto # The port of the remote (Java Edition) server # For plugin versions, if address has been set to "auto", the port will also follow the server's listening port. port: 25565 # Authentication type. Can be offline, online, or floodgate (see https://github.com/GeyserMC/Geyser/wiki/Floodgate). # For plugin versions, it's recommended to keep the `address` field to "auto" so Floodgate support is automatically configured. # If Floodgate is installed and `address:` is set to "auto", then "auth-type: floodgate" will automatically be used. auth-type: online # Allow for password-based authentication methods through Geyser. Only useful in online mode. # If this is false, users must authenticate to Microsoft using a code provided by Geyser on their desktop. allow-password-authentication: true # Whether to enable PROXY protocol or not while connecting to the server. # This is useful only when: # 1) Your server supports PROXY protocol (it probably doesn't) # 2) You run Velocity or BungeeCord with the option enabled in the proxy's main config. # IF YOU DON'T KNOW WHAT THIS IS, DON'T TOUCH IT! use-proxy-protocol: false # Forward the hostname that the Bedrock client used to connect over to the Java server # This is designed to be used for forced hosts on proxies forward-hostname: false
# Floodgate uses encryption to ensure use from authorised sources. # This should point to the public key generated by Floodgate (BungeeCord, Spigot or Velocity) # You can ignore this when not using Floodgate. # If you're using a plugin version of Floodgate on the same server, the key will automatically be picked up from Floodgate. floodgate-key-file: key.pem
# For online mode authentication type only. # Stores a list of Bedrock players that should have their Java Edition account saved after login. # This saves a token that can be reused to authenticate the player later. This does not save emails or passwords, # but you should still be cautious when adding to this list and giving others access to this Geyser instance's files. # Removing a name from this list will delete its cached login information on the next Geyser startup. # The file for this is in the same folder as this config, named "saved-refresh-tokens.json". saved-user-logins: - ThisExampleUsernameShouldBeLongEnoughToNeverBeAnXboxUsername - ThisOtherExampleUsernameShouldAlsoBeLongEnough
# Specify how many seconds to wait while user authorizes Geyser to access their Microsoft account. # User is allowed to disconnect from the server during this period. pending-authentication-timeout: 120
# Bedrock clients can freeze when opening up the command prompt for the first time if given a lot of commands. # Disabling this will prevent command suggestions from being sent and solve freezing for Bedrock clients. command-suggestions: true
# The following three options enable "ping passthrough" - the MOTD, player count and/or protocol name gets retrieved from the Java server. # Relay the MOTD from the remote server to Bedrock players. passthrough-motd: false # Relay the protocol name (e.g. BungeeCord [X.X], Paper 1.X) - only really useful when using a custom protocol name! # This will also show up on sites like MCSrvStatus. <mcsrvstat.us> passthrough-protocol-name: false # Relay the player count and max players from the remote server to Bedrock players. passthrough-player-counts: false # Enable LEGACY ping passthrough. There is no need to enable this unless your MOTD or player count does not appear properly. # This option does nothing on standalone. legacy-ping-passthrough: false # How often to ping the remote server, in seconds. Only relevant for standalone or legacy ping passthrough. # Increase if you are getting BrokenPipe errors. ping-passthrough-interval: 3
# Whether to forward player ping to the server. While enabling this will allow Bedrock players to have more accurate # ping, it may also cause players to time out more easily. forward-player-ping: false
# Maximum amount of players that can connect. This is only visual at this time and does not actually limit player count. max-players: $[Service.Slots]
# If debug messages should be sent through console debug-mode: false
# Allow third party capes to be visible. Currently allowing: # OptiFine capes, LabyMod capes, 5Zig capes and MinecraftCapes allow-third-party-capes: true
# Allow third party deadmau5 ears to be visible. Currently allowing: # MinecraftCapes allow-third-party-ears: false
# Allow a fake cooldown indicator to be sent. Bedrock players do not see a cooldown as they still use 1.8 combat # Can be title, actionbar or false show-cooldown: title
# Controls if coordinates are shown to players. show-coordinates: true
# Whether Bedrock players are blocked from performing their scaffolding-style bridging. disable-bedrock-scaffolding: false
# Whether Bedrock players can right-click outside of their inventory to replace armor in their inventory, even if the # armor slot is already occupied (which Java Edition doesn't allow) always-quick-change-armor: false
# If set, when a Bedrock player performs any emote, it will swap the offhand and mainhand items, just like the Java Edition keybind # There are three options this can be set to: # disabled - the default/fallback, which doesn't apply this workaround # no-emotes - emotes will NOT be sent to other Bedrock clients and offhand will be swapped. This effectively disables all emotes from being seen. # emotes-and-offhand - emotes will be sent to Bedrock clients and offhand will be swapped emote-offhand-workaround: "disabled"
# The default locale if we dont have the one the client requested. Uncomment to not use the default system language. # default-locale: en_us
# Specify how many days images will be cached to disk to save downloading them from the internet. # A value of 0 is disabled. (Default: 0) cache-images: 0
# Allows custom skulls to be displayed. Keeping them enabled may cause a performance decrease on older/weaker devices. allow-custom-skulls: true
# Whether to add (at this time, only) the furnace minecart as a separate item in the game, which normally does not exist in Bedrock Edition. # This should only need to be disabled if using a proxy that does not use the "transfer packet" style of server switching. # If this is disabled, furnace minecart items will be mapped to hopper minecart items. # This option requires a restart of Geyser in order to change its setting. add-non-bedrock-items: true
# Bedrock prevents building and displaying blocks above Y127 in the Nether. # This config option works around that by changing the Nether dimension ID to the End ID. # The main downside to this is that the entire Nether will have the same red fog rather than having different fog for each biome. above-bedrock-nether-building: false
# Force clients to load all resource packs if there are any. # If set to false, it allows the user to connect to the server even if they don't # want to download the resource packs. force-resource-packs: true
# Allows Xbox achievements to be unlocked. # THIS DISABLES ALL COMMANDS FROM SUCCESSFULLY RUNNING FOR BEDROCK IN-GAME, as otherwise Bedrock thinks you are cheating. xbox-achievements-enabled: false
# bStats is a stat tracker that is entirely anonymous and tracks only basic information # about Geyser, such as how many people are online, how many servers are using Geyser, # what OS is being used, etc. You can learn more about bStats here: https://bstats.org/. # https://bstats.org/plugin/server-implementation/GeyserMC metrics: # If metrics should be enabled enabled: true # UUID of server, don't change! uuid: ![GeyserUUID]
# ADVANCED OPTIONS - DO NOT TOUCH UNLESS YOU KNOW WHAT YOU ARE DOING!
# Geyser updates the Scoreboard after every Scoreboard packet, but when Geyser tries to handle # a lot of scoreboard packets per second can cause serious lag. # This option allows you to specify after how many Scoreboard packets per seconds # the Scoreboard updates will be limited to four updates per second. scoreboard-packet-threshold: 20
# Allow connections from ProxyPass and Waterdog. # See https://www.spigotmc.org/wiki/firewall-guide/ for assistance - use UDP instead of TCP. enable-proxy-connections: false
# The internet supports a maximum MTU of 1492 but could cause issues with packet fragmentation. # 1400 is the default. mtu: 1400
# Whether to connect directly into the Java server without creating a TCP connection. # This should only be disabled if a plugin that interfaces with packets or the network does not work correctly with Geyser. # If enabled on plugin versions, the remote address and port sections are ignored # If disabled on plugin versions, expect performance decrease and latency increase use-direct-connection: true
config-version: 4

tc_game_scripts.description: Downloads and installs Java binaries from Adoptium
tc_game_scripts.script_contents:
# This script is also run on After Created and After Reinstall. If you need to make any changes, make them in this script.
import clr clr.AddReference('System.IO') from System.IO import Path, Directory, File from System.Net import WebClient from zipfile import ZipFile import tarfile from os import environ from System import Environment, PlatformID from TCAdmin.SDK.Misc import CompressionTools from System.Runtime.InteropServices import RuntimeInformation
#Check if run as a scheduled task. We check if ThisTaskStep.WriteLog is callable. If it is, set WriteLog = ThisTaskStep.WriteLog. If it isn't, set WriteLog = WriteLog. try: ThisTaskStep.WriteLog except NameError: WriteLog = Script.WriteToConsole else: WriteLog = ThisTaskStep.WriteLog
# Set service to processing ThisService.Variables['Processing'] = "True" ThisService.Configure()
java_folder = Path.Combine(ThisService.RootDirectory, 'java')
os = 'windows' if Environment.OSVersion.Platform == PlatformID.Win32NT else 'linux' arch = 'aarch64' if str(RuntimeInformation.ProcessArchitecture) =='Arm64' else 'x64' #WriteLog("Operating system is {0} Architecture is {1}".format(os, arch)) #Should you want to use another API to grab the Java binaries, replace the urls in the following section java8 = { 'version':'8', 'url':'https://api.adoptium.net/v3/binary/latest/8/ga/{0}/{1}/jdk/hotspot/normal/eclipse?project=jdk'.format(os, arch) } java11 = { 'version':'11', 'url':'https://api.adoptium.net/v3/binary/latest/11/ga/{0}/{1}/jdk/hotspot/normal/eclipse?project=jdk'.format(os, arch) } java16 = { 'version':'16', 'url':'https://api.adoptium.net/v3/binary/latest/16/ga/{0}/{1}/jdk/hotspot/normal/eclipse?project=jdk'.format(os, arch) } java17 = { 'version':'17', 'url':'https://api.adoptium.net/v3/binary/latest/17/ga/{0}/{1}/jdk/hotspot/normal/eclipse?project=jdk'.format(os, arch) } urls = [java8, java11, java16, java17]
#Create the java folder if it doesn't exist if not Directory.Exists(java_folder): Directory.CreateDirectory(java_folder)
try: wc = WebClient() for adoptium in urls: #Only download binaries for non-installed versions of Java (environment variables must be set as JAVA8, JAVA11 and JAVA16) if 'JAVA{version}'.format(version=adoptium['version']) in environ: WriteLog('Skipping downloading '+adoptium['version']+' as env variable exists') continue #Delete folder if it exists (ie /java/jre16) when we need to update if Directory.Exists(Path.Combine(java_folder,'java'+adoptium['version'])): Directory.Delete(Path.Combine(java_folder,'java'+adoptium['version']), True) WriteLog('{} has been deleted before update'.format(Path.Combine('java', 'java'+adoptium['version'])))
archive_type = '.zip' if Environment.OSVersion.Platform == PlatformID.Win32NT else '.tar.gz' archive_name = 'adoptium'+adoptium['version']+archive_type
WriteLog('Downloading ' + archive_name)
#Download archive file try: wc.DownloadFile(adoptium['url'], Path.Combine(java_folder, archive_name)) except Exception, e: WriteLog('Something went wrong: {}'.format(e))
#Extract archive (WIndows) if archive_name.endswith(".zip"): with ZipFile(Path.Combine(java_folder, archive_name), 'r') as zipObj: foldername =zipObj.filelist[0].filename if Directory.Exists(Path.Combine(java_folder, foldername)): Directory.Delete(Path.Combine(java_folder, foldername), True) WriteLog('Extracting '+archive_name) zipObj.extractall(java_folder) WriteLog('All files extracted') WriteLog('Renaming directory to '+Path.Combine('java', 'java'+adoptium['version'])) Directory.Move(Path.Combine(java_folder, foldername), Path.Combine(java_folder, 'java'+adoptium['version']))
#Extract archive (Linux) elif archive_name.endswith("tar.gz"): #We only need tarfile to see the name of the folder in the archive. tarfile.extractall() causes issues on Linux tar = tarfile.open(Path.Combine(java_folder, archive_name), "r:gz") foldername = tar.next().name tar.close() if Directory.Exists(Path.Combine(java_folder, foldername)): Directory.Delete(Path.Combine(java_folder, foldername), True) WriteLog('Extracting '+archive_name) c=CompressionTools() c.Decompress(Path.Combine(java_folder, archive_name), java_folder) WriteLog('All files extracted') WriteLog('Renaming directory to '+Path.Combine(java_folder, 'java'+adoptium['version'])) Directory.Move(Path.Combine(java_folder, foldername), Path.Combine(java_folder, 'java'+adoptium['version']))
#Delete archive files if File.Exists(Path.Combine(java_folder, archive_name)): try: File.Delete(Path.Combine(java_folder, archive_name)) except IOError, e: WriteLog('Could not delete %s:' % (archive_name, e))
#If anything goes wrong, set Processing to False except Exception, e: WriteLog('Something went wrong, aborting: {}'.format(e)) ThisService.Variables['Processing'] = "False" ThisService.Configure()
# Set processing to false ThisService.Variables['Processing'] = "False" ThisService.Configure() WriteLog('Java configuration has finished')

tc_game_scripts.script_contents:
from System import Environment, PlatformID from platform import system import os
entrypointMappings = { "Java 8": "java8", "Java 11": "java11", "Java 16": "java16", }
java_folder = os.path.join(ThisService.RootDirectory, 'java') executable = '.exe' if system() == 'Windows' else '' content = ' %*' if system() == 'Windows' else ' $*' bash_shebang = '#!/bin/bash\n' if system() == 'Linux' else '' #On Linux, we need to add a shebang at the top of the .sh file
if entrypointMappings['Java 16'].upper() in os.environ: #If environment variables exists, use them java_path = '\"%'+entrypointMappings['Java 16'].upper()+'%\"' if system() == 'Windows' else '\"${'+entrypointMappings['Java 16'].upper()+'}\"' elif entrypointMappings['Java 11'].upper() in os.environ: java_path = '\"%'+entrypointMappings['Java 11'].upper()+'%\"' if system() == 'Windows' else '\"${'+entrypointMappings['Java 11'].upper()+'}\"' elif entrypointMappings['Java 8'].upper() in os.environ: java_path = '\"%'+entrypointMappings['Java 8'].upper()+'%\"' if system() == 'Windows' else '\"${'+entrypointMappings['Java 8'].upper()+'}\"' elif os.path.isfile(os.path.join(java_folder, entrypointMappings['Java 16'], 'bin', 'java'+executable)): #If no environment variables exists, check if Java binaries exists on the service java_path = os.path.join(java_folder, entrypointMappings['Java 16'], 'bin', 'java'+executable) elif os.path.isfile(os.path.join(java_folder, entrypointMappings['Java 11'], 'bin', 'java'+executable)): java_path = os.path.join(java_folder, entrypointMappings['Java 11'], 'bin', 'java'+executable) elif os.path.isfile(os.path.join(java_folder, entrypointMappings['Java 8'], 'bin', 'java'+executable)): java_path = os.path.join(java_folder, entrypointMappings['Java 8'], 'bin', 'java'+executable) else: #Fallback to using 'java' java_path = 'java'
#Write the java path to the executable file with open(ThisService.Executable, 'w') as file: file.write(bash_shebang + java_path + content)

tc_game_scripts.description: Check if EULA is set to true before start
tc_game_scripts.script_contents:
from System.IO import File, Path from System.Text.RegularExpressions import Regex, RegexOptions from System import Environment, PlatformID, String
eulafile = Path.Combine(ThisService_RootDirectory, String.Format("eula.txt"))
pattern="eula=(?<eula>(true|false)*)?" filecontents = File.ReadAllText(eulafile) match = Regex.Match(filecontents, pattern, RegexOptions.IgnoreCase)
if match.Groups["eula"].Value != "true": raise Exception("You need to accept the EULA. Open eula.txt and set eula=true in the file.");

import json, urllib2, os from System import Version from System.Net import WebClient
request = urllib2.Request('https://api.github.com/repos/CreeperHost/Log4jPatcher/releases/latest') response = urllib2.urlopen(request) json_info = json.load(response)
log4jpatcher_version = json_info['name'] log4jpatcher_version_latest = Version(json_info['name']) try: log4jpatcher_version_installed = Version(ThisService_Log4jPatcherVersion) except NameError: log4jpatcher_version_installed = Version('0.0.0')
if log4jpatcher_version_installed.CompareTo(log4jpatcher_version_latest) < 0: Script.WriteToConsole('Service {} - Updating Log4jPatcher before startup'.format(ThisService_ServiceId)) wc = WebClient() try: destination_file = os.path.join(ThisService_RootDirectory, 'Log4jPatcher', 'Log4jPatcher.jar') destination_path = os.path.dirname(destination_file) if not os.path.exists(destination_path): os.mkdir(destination_path) wc.DownloadFile(json_info['assets'][0]['browser_download_url'], destination_file) ThisService_Log4jPatcherVersion = log4jpatcher_version ThisServiceController.ServiceConfig["Service.CommandLineArguments"] = '-javaagent:Log4jPatcher/Log4jPatcher.jar ' + ThisServiceController.ServiceConfig["Service.CommandLineArguments"] ThisService.Save() Script.WriteToConsole('Service {} - Log4jPatcher has been updated'.format(ThisService_ServiceId)) except Exception as e: Script.WriteToConsole('Service {} - Failed to download {}: {}'.format(ThisService_ServiceId, json_info['assets'][0]['name'], e))

tc_game_scripts.description: Creates a backup of your world
tc_game_scripts.script_contents:
import clr # Add reference to System.IO.Compression.FileSystem so we can use ZipFile clr.AddReference('System.IO.Compression.FileSystem') from datetime import datetime from System.IO import Directory, Path, DirectoryInfo, File clr.AddReference("System.Core") import System clr.ImportExtensions(System.Linq) from System.IO.Compression import ZipFile
# Settings max_backups = 10 #Specify how many backups a user can have per service
# Get current date and time now = datetime.now()
# Check if backup path exists, create directory if it does not
backupPath = ThisService.RootDirectory + 'Backups/' if not Directory.Exists(backupPath): Script.WriteToConsole('Creating Backup folder...') Directory.CreateDirectory(backupPath)
# Check current number of backups backup_files = DirectoryInfo(backupPath).GetFiles('*.zip').OrderByDescending(lambda f: f.CreationTime)
for file in backup_files.Skip(max_backups - 1): file_path = Path.Combine(backupPath, file.Name) if File.Exists(file_path): try: Script.WriteToConsole('Max number of backups reached. Deleting oldest backup: {}'.format(file.Name)) File.Delete(file_path) except IOError, e: Script.WriteToConsole('Failed to delete {}, error was: {}'.format(file.Name, e))
# Create an archive of the selected world Script.WriteToConsole('Making a backup of world \'' + str(ThisService.Variables['BackupWorld']) + '\'...') try: ZipFile.CreateFromDirectory(Path.Combine(ThisService.RootDirectory, ThisService.Variables['BackupWorld']), Path.Combine(backupPath, ThisService.Variables['BackupWorld'] + now.strftime('%Y-%m-%d_%H%M%S') +'.zip')) Script.WriteToConsole('Backup successfully created') except Exception as e: raise Exception('Could not create zip file: {}'.format(e))

import clr clr.AddReference('System.IO.Compression.FileSystem') from datetime import datetime from System.IO.Compression import ZipFile from System.IO import Directory, Path from System import Environment, PlatformID from TCAdmin.SDK.Misc import CompressionTools, Linux, Windows
now = datetime.now() backup_file = ThisService.Variables['BackupWorldLoad'] year = now.strftime('%Y') foldername = str(backup_file.split(year, 1)[0])
if Directory.Exists(Path.Combine(ThisService.RootDirectory, foldername)): Directory.Delete(Path.Combine(ThisService.RootDirectory, foldername), 'True') Script.WriteToConsole('Deleted the world folder: ' + foldername)
Script.WriteToConsole('Extracting backup: ' + backup_file + '...') ZipFile.ExtractToDirectory(ThisService.RootDirectory + 'Backups/' + ThisService.Variables['BackupWorldLoad'], ThisService.RootDirectory + foldername) Script.WriteToConsole('Backup extracted') if Environment.OSVersion.Platform == PlatformID.Unix : if Linux.IsRoot() : Script.WriteToConsole('Setting correct permissions on extracted folder...') Linux.SetDirectoryOwnerAutoDetect(ThisService.RootDirectory + foldername, True) else : owner = Windows.GetOwner(ThisService.RootDirectory) Script.WriteToConsole('Setting correct permissions on extracted folder...') Windows.SetDirectoryOwner(ThisService.RootDirectory + foldername, str(owner), True) Script.WriteToConsole('Backup has been restored')

tc_game_variables_config.description:
Automatically decide: Allow the control panel to decide the Java version used to start the server based on certain checks. This is recommended but might not work all the time.

Java 8: Start the server using Java 8 (Temurin JDK 8) every time.

Java 11: Start the server using Java 11 (Temurin JDK 11) every time.

Java 16: Start the server using Java 16 (Temurin JDK 16) every time.

Java 17: Start the server using Java 17 (Temurin JDK 17) every time.

Please note that some versions of Minecraft will require a specific version of Java. If you are having trouble starting your server, try changing the Java version.

tc_dynamic_form_items.description:
This is the message that is displayed in the server list of the client, below the name.
  • The MOTD supports color and formatting codes.
  • The MOTD supports special characters, such as "♥". However, such characters must be converted to escaped Unicode form. An online converter can be found here.
  • If the MOTD is over 59 characters, the server list may report a communication error.

tc_dynamic_form_items.description: Server checks connecting players against Minecraft account database. Set this to false only if the player's server is not connected to the Internet. Hackers with fake accounts can connect if this is set to false! If minecraft.net is down or inaccessible, no players can connect if this is set to true. Setting this variable to off purposely is called "cracking" a server, and servers that are present with online mode off are called "cracked" servers, allowing players with unlicensed copies of Minecraft to join. true - Enabled. The server assumes it has an Internet connection and checks every connecting player. false - Disabled. The server does not attempt to check connecting players.

tc_dynamic_form_items.description:
Determines the type of map‌ (until JE 1.19) / the world preset‌ (after JE 1.19) that is generated.

Escaping ":" is required when using a world preset ID, and the vanilla world preset ID's namespace (minecraft:) can be omitted (after JE 1.19).

default‌ (until JE 1.19) / minecraft:normal‌ (after JE 1.19) - Standard world with hills, valleys, water, etc.

flat‌ (until JE 1.19) / minecraft:flat‌ (after JE 1.19) - A flat world with no features, can be modified with generator-settings.

largeBiomes‌ (until JE 1.19) / minecraft:large_biomes‌ (after JE 1.19) - Same as default but all biomes are larger.

amplified‌ (until JE 1.19) / minecraft:amplified‌ (after JE 1.19) - Same as default but world-generation height limit is increased.

minecraft:single_biome_surface‌ (after JE 1.19) - A buffet world which the entire overworld consists of one biome, can be modified with generator-settings.

buffet - Only for 1.15 or before. Same as default unless generator-settings is set.

default_1_1 - Only for 1.15 or before. Same as default, but counted as a different world type.

customized - Only for 1.15 or before. After 1.13, this value is no different than default, but in 1.12 and before, it could be used to create a completely custom world.

This sets the maximum possible size in blocks, expressed as a radius, that the world border can obtain. Setting the world border bigger causes the commands to complete successfully but the actual border does not move past this block limit. tc_dynamic_form_items.description: By default it allows packets that are n-1 bytes big to go normally, but a packet of n bytes or more gets compressed down. So, a lower number means more compression but compressing small amounts of bytes might actually end up with a larger result than what went in. -1 - disable compression entirely 0 - compress everything Note: The Ethernet spec requires that packets less than 64 bytes become padded to 64 bytes. Thus, setting a value lower than 64 may not be beneficial. It is also not recommended to exceed the MTU, typically 1500 bytes.

Sets the maximum distance from players that living entities may be located in order to be updated by the server, measured in chunks in each direction of the player (radius, not diameter). If entities are outside of this radius, then they will not be ticked by the server nor will they be visible to players.
10 is the default/recommended. If the player has major lag, this value is recommended to be reduced.
